.IX Title "Plagger::Rule::Fresh 3"
.TH Plagger::Rule::Fresh 3 "2006-12-05" "perl v5.8.9" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.SH "NAME"
Plagger::Rule::Fresh \- Rule to find 'fresh' entries or feeds
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 7
\&  # entries updated within 120 minutes
\&  - module: SmartFeed
\&    config:
\&      id: fresh-entries
\&    rule:
\&      module: Fresh
\&      duration: 120
.Ve
.PP
.Vb 7
\&  # remove entries older than mtime of /tmp/foo.tmp
\&  - module: Filter::Rule
\&    rule:
\&      module: Fresh
\&      mtime:
\&        path: /tmp/foo.tmp
\&        autoupdate: 1
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This rule finds fresh entries or feeds, which means updated date is
within \f(CW\*(C`duration\*(C'\fR minutes. It defaults to 2 hours, but you'd better
configure the value with your cronjob interval.
.SH "CONFIG"
.IX Header "CONFIG"
.ie n .IP """duration""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWduration\fR" 4
.IX Item "duration"
.Vb 1
\&  duration: 5
.Ve
.Sp
This rule matches with entries posted within 5 minutes. When you
invoke \f(CW\*(C`plagger\*(C'\fR script in cronjob, you'd better specify the
same \f(CW\*(C`duration\*(C'\fR variable with the job interval.
.Sp
If the supplied value contains only digit, it's parsed as minutes. You
can write in a human readable format like:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&  duration: 4 hours
.Ve
.Sp
and this module DWIMs. It defaults to \fI120\fR, which means 2 hours.
.ie n .IP """mtime""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWmtime\fR" 4
.IX Item "mtime"
.Vb 3
\&  mtime:
\&    path: /path/to/mtime.file
\&    autoupdate: 1
.Ve
.Sp
This rule matches with entries newer than mtime of
\&\f(CW\*(C`/path/to/mtime.file\*(C'\fR. If \f(CW\*(C`autoupdate\*(C'\fR option is set (default is
off), this plugin automatically creates and updates the file in plugin
registration phase.
